@article{Famulari2018,
abstract = {Purpose: Despite the importance of peer review for brachytherapy plans, human errors could occur. An incorrect programming time can easily result in medical events. Thus, to detect incorrect plan such as abnormal radiation time and isodose volumes before treatment delivery, we further developed a tool of independent check of brachytherapy plans. To accurately predict total radiation time, we performed correlation analysis between clinical target volume (CTV) and total reference air kerma (TRAK) in CT-based HDR interstitial brachytherapy. Furthermore, the volumes enclosed by the isodoses, numbers of implanted catheters, and active dwells were estimated with the CTV. Materials and Methods: The study includes 164 interstitial brachytherapy patients for gynecologic malignancies including cervical, endometrial and vaginal cancers treated between January 2011 and May 2017 at our institution. Under ultrasound guidance, Flexi-Guide needles were implanted into the target with the Syed-Neblett template. Then 3D CT simulation scan was performed for treatment planning. Target (high-risk CTV) and OARs (bladder, rectum, sigmoid, and bowel) were contoured on CT using Elekta Oncentra Brachy TPS. 4.5-7 Gy per fraction in 4-10 fractions were prescribed to the HR-CTV. Treatment plans were generated using IPSA optimization to meet target coverage (CTV D 90 O 100{\%}, V 100 O 97{\%}, and V 150 ! 35{\%}) and OAR constraints (D2cc ! 70-75 Gy to the rectum, sigmoid, and bowel and D2cc ! 90 Gy to the bladder in term of EQD2 for combined EBRT and BT). V CTV , V 90{\%} , V 100{\%} , V 150{\%} , V 200{\%} , and TRAK normalized with the fractional dose (d) were acquired from the TPS. The relations between the DVH parameters were calculated using linear and quadratic functions and evaluated with the coefficient of determination (R 2). Total radiation time (T) and treated volumes were then predicted using the model with a given V CTV , d, and air kerma strength (S k) and compared to the actual radiation time and V 100{\%} from the TPS. Results: Linear regression (number of implant catheters 5 0.0858{\$}V CTV þ 13.55 (R 2 50.6088)) shows that the target volume (92.2 AE 58.9 cm 3 , range: 20.1-343.6 cm 3) have a weak correlation with the number of catheters. Furthermore, a linear regression (active dwells 5 1.7303{\$}V CTV þ 64.342 (R 2 5 0.8593)) shows a strong correlation between the number of active dwells and V CTV. A quadratic regression (TRAK/d 5-0.00005{\$}V 2 CTV þ 0.054V CTV þ 1.9448 (R 2 50.9739)) and linear regression (V 100{\%} 51.1199V CTV þ 9.4793 (R 2 50.9881)) show that TRAK/d and V 100{\%} have a very strong correlation with V CTV. Total radiation times for the given V CTV were predicted with T (sec) 5 (TRAK/d){\$}(d/S k){\$}(3600 sec/h), where TRAK is in cGy cm 2 , d is in cGy, S k is in cGy{\$}cm 2 /h, and V 100{\%} and V CTV are in cm 3. The mean {\%} difference between the actual and the predicted radiation time was-0.18AE5.95{\%} (range:-16.3-19.5{\%}). The mean {\%} difference between the actual and the predicted treated volume was-0.74AE6.47{\%} (range:-18.8-18.3{\%}). Conclusions: We found that TRAK/d, treated volume, and the number of active dwells have a strong correlation with the target volume. Total radiation time could be accurately predicted with the target volume, prescription dose, and source strength. In order to detect abnormal radiation time and treated volume in CT-based HDR interstitial gynecologic brachytherapy, this method could be used for an essential part of quality assurance (QA) procedures. Purpose: To present RapidBrachyMCTPS, a novel and complete treatment planning system for brachytherapy applications with an inverse planning optimization algorithm coupled to a Geant4-based Monte Carlo (MC) dose calculation engine. Materials and Methods: We have developed a user friendly graphical user interface based Monte Carlo dose planning software with capabilities to import tumour site specific applicators in 